
[1]proffer

   PROF'FER, v.t. [L. profero; pro and fero, to bear.]

   1. To offer for acceptance; as, to proffer a gift; to proffer services;
   to proffer friendship.

   2. To essay or attempt of one's own accord.

   None

   So hardy as to proffer or accept

   Alone the dreadful voyage.

      PROF'FER, n. An offer made; something proposed for acceptance by
                another; as proffers of peace or friendship.

   He made a proffer to lay down his commission of command in the army.

   1. Essay; attempt.
